A Republican strategy to counter Obama's re-election
Republican leaders justified their policies by the need to combat electoral fraud.
However, the Brennan Centre considers the latter a myth, claiming that electoral fraud is rarer in the United States than the number of people killed by lightning.
Indeed, Republican lawyers have recorded only 300 cases of electoral fraud in the United States in ten years.
One thing is certain: these new provisions will have a negative impact on the participation rate.
In this sense, these measures will in part undermine the American democratic system.
Unlike Canada, the U.S. states are responsible for organizing federal elections in the U.S.
It is in this spirit that a majority of US governments enacted new laws from 2009 making the registration or voting process more difficult.
This phenomenon grew after the November 2010 elections, which added 675 new Republican representatives to 26 states.
As a result, 180 draft laws restricting the exercise of the right to vote in 41 states were introduced in 2011 alone.
New electoral laws require voters to present a photo ID card and proof of U.S. citizenship.
In addition, these laws also reduce advance voting periods, invalidate the right to register as an elector on polling day and remove the right to vote from citizens with judicial records.
Prior to the 2006 elections, no U.S. state required voters to present a photo ID card.
Indiana was the first state to impose such a requirement.
The U.S. Supreme Court confirmed the constitutionality of Indiana's law in 2008.
The Republican authorities hastened to extend this practice to other states.
Over the past two years, they have sponsored bills in 34 states to force voters to present photo ID cards.
It is important to note that, unlike Quebec, U.S. citizens do not have universal identity cards such as the health insurance card.
Indeed, 11% of U.S. citizens, or 21 million people of voting age, do not have photo ID cards issued by a government agency in their state.
In addition, five million new voters in 2012 do not have such identification.
However, it often costs more than a hundred dollars to obtain the required identity card.
The new restrictions disproportionately affect young people, minorities and low-income people.
Indeed, 25% of African Americans, 15% of people earning less than $35,000; 18% of citizens over 65 years of age and 20% of voters between 18 and 29 years of age do not have the required photo ID card.
Much more.
Students, voters considered to be voting more for Democratic candidates, are not allowed in several states to use their photo ID card issued by their institution.
On the other hand, these same states allow members of fishing or hunting clubs who vote more on the Republican side to use the cards issued by these clubs to vote.
Prior to 2004, no state required proof of citizenship to vote.
Arizona was the first to present such a requirement.
Since 2011, a dozen states have passed laws requiring voters to prove that they are American citizens.
These measures are clearly aimed at limiting Hispanic voting.
However, it appears that two out of three Hispanic voters favour the Democratic Party.
In addition, Republican legislators in 2011 sponsored laws abolishing voter registration on election day in eight states.
In addition, they limited the right of individuals and groups to provide assistance to electors wishing to register.
These restrictions are not without consequence.
For example, in the 2004 general election, voter registration campaigns helped to register approximately 10 million citizens.
However, measures adopted since 2009 have led to a 17% drop in the registration rate of new voters in 2010 compared to 2006.
In addition, Republican legislators have passed laws in five other states aimed at reducing the advance voting period.
For example, in the 2008 general election in Florida, 33% of the voters who voted in advance were African-Americans, while the latter accounted for only 13% of the state's voters.
The same was true with Hispanics.
They represented only 11% of voters, but 24% of citizens who voted in advance.
In return, the whites who made up 76% of the voters represented only 46% of the voters voting in advance.
Of course, democratic legislators and their supporters strongly opposed the adoption of laws restricting voter registration.
Several bills have been blocked by the vetoes of the democrat governors.
The US Attorney General intervened to suspend the most controversial laws.
They may have partially limited the damage.
For example, only 16 out of 34 States have enacted legislation requiring the presentation of photo ID cards.
Nevertheless, the new rules introduced will undoubtedly make it more difficult to exercise the right to vote in 2012.
Democratic critics denounce the partisan nature of the laws that have been passed and see it as a clear objective to influence the results in 2012 in key states.
A 2011 Brennan Centre report shows that the states that passed these laws represent 171 of the 270 votes necessary for the electoral college to win the presidency.
It is too early to say with certainty that these legislative changes in the electoral system will have a significant impact on the outcome of the 2012 presidential elections.
But one thing is certain: these new provisions will have a negative impact on the participation rate.
In this sense, these measures will in part undermine the American democratic system.
