We began to focus on the issues of reproduction in space by focusing on flora.
Half a century ago, we were experimenting on plants.
Four generations of small peas grown in orbit did not differ in any way from earth varieties.
Then we put in orbit insects, small breeding drosophilic flies.
In 1979, quail eggs were sent to space to see how an embryo was developing in weightlessness.
We get a perfectly normal chick at the exit.
Then the problems begin.
"The problem is that the chick has to find a support, he has to get on his feet and start moving," explains the director of the laboratory of the Institute of Medical and Biological Problems of the Russian Academy of Sciences (IMBP) Vladimir Sychev.
By not finding any support, the chicks were agitated in a disorderly manner.
And after 10 hours, the newborns saw their instincts completely atrophying.
The chicks did not react to light or sound.
Unfortunately, they would simply die after four days.
"We shook their eyes twice, then we gave up, because it is simply impossible to work with them there," explains Vladimir Sychev, noting the failure of the experiment with chicks in space.
The last biological "miniature arch" with animals was sent to orbit 16 years ago.
The experiments will continue in the spring of 2013.
However, the "Bion" biosatellite will only ship species of the same sex.
There was an experiment with rats sent with their fetuses into space.
In principle, nothing supernatural has been discovered.
"They were still biosatellites and then it's the only experiment. We have to do this kind of research," notes Vladimir Sychev.
After landing, space rats gave birth to their offspring.
However, reproductions are not yet possible directly in space.
It's no small deal.
By losing their usual environment, animals are no longer able to realize their sexual instincts.
Unlike beasts, man is capable of it, in principle.
Homo sapiens possess abstract thought, he is able to create an appropriate emotional background.
This type of experiment is not carried out for ethical reasons.
But women have been in space for 50 years.
The biggest risk was taken by Tereshkova.
And the feminine organism is what humanity has most precious.
Our seagull flew away and no one on Earth could say if it would stand after a flight into space.
If she could have given birth to a child after the robbery.
