At the meeting of the Monitoring Committee in the Chamber of Deputies, you mentioned a Czech-German project in which the public procurement legislation of these two countries was compared.
What was the concrete question?
This is a parallel control that we launched about two years ago.
In simple terms, European legislation provides for the way in which public procurement and specific national legislation and practice follow it.
We have gathered all this together and although this monitoring procedure has not yet been completed, very interesting differences have appeared to us: generally speaking, our legislation is perhaps "more stringent and of better quality", nevertheless, according to certain parameters, practice as such is better in Germany.
This confirms, therefore, that it is not enough to continually develop increasingly detailed rules but that it is necessary to devote itself to the very implementation of the law.
How can this project help you concretely and what does it result for you?
Common control of this kind should help us stop trying to clarify laws, lower and improve thresholds, when this does not have a really positive effect.
The principle of good management means getting the thing in question at a reasonable price (which does not always mean the lowest), in order to exclude any enrichment and possible criminal activity.
But lowering market thresholds will not necessarily achieve this goal.
It may be that this system is so overwhelmed by red tape that those looking for loopholes will find much more opportunities than if the threshold had remained higher.
You are talking about internal problems concerning the implementation of public procurement legislation.
How does the control system work in Germany?
Is there an institution similar to our SAI or a different method of organization?
As far as the institutions are concerned, as in the case of the SAI, the Bundesrechnungshof, which is organised in a similar way, also has a council set up a little differently, but these two institutions basically proceed in a similar way.
The competences are also, to a certain extent, similar, however, with a nuance vis-à-vis our system: since Germany is a federal structure, it therefore also has such prices of accounts at the level of the various Länder.
The ORH can only control federal money, which in our case corresponds to the resources of the state.
The public funds managed at home by the regions and municipalities are controlled there at the level of the Länder's accounts.
As far as national legislation is concerned, is it simpler than ours?
I would not like to make a general comparison without concrete data, however, in some areas Germany is often referred to as a model, but it certainly cannot be said that it does better in all areas.
Maybe it's because they have better detectives?
No, certainly not, but I repeat, I don't have any comparative data.
However, it must also be said that this country, which we see as a model, is also faced with a whole range of problems.
Otherwise they wouldn't have any advantage in cooperating with our institution, would they?
As far as national legislation is concerned, what has been meant for you, as an institution, by the amendment of the law on public procurement, are its effects already being felt?
