Poland and the cosmos.
Last week, at the meeting of ministers of the European Space Agency countries, Poland was admitted as 20th member of the Agency, it is the second member State of the former Eastern bloc (the Czech Republic became a full member on 12 November 2008).
Poland had started close cooperation with ESA in 1994 and in the years that followed participated in a number of the Agency's projects.
However, Poland's journey to space began much earlier.
Already before the Second World War, passionate Poles were working on space flights; they did not always meet with understanding.
I would like to mention, for example, the conference of A. Šternfeld at the Warsaw Astronomical Observatory on 6 December 1933, at which he presented ideas from his avant-garde work entitled "Introduction to Astronautics".
The developments of this young engineer (born 1905) left the listeners cold and years later Šternfeld remembered that only Dr.Jan Gadomski was interested in his work.
In 1934 Šternfeld won the Robert Esnault-Pelterie and André Louis Hirsch Prize in France for his work "Introduction à l'astronautique".
Dr.Jan Gadomski (1899 - 1966) later became a great promoter of astronomy and astronautics.
He published hundreds of articles in Polish newspapers and wrote many books devoted to this scientific discipline.
Gadomski became a propagator of the world-renowned astronautic, his contribution was especially rewarded by the fact that his name was given to one of the craters of the hidden face of the Moon.
As early as 1925, a draisine was built in Poland to be equipped with a rocket engine.
Unfortunately, neither the author nor the details of this project are known.
It is also unclear whether the rocket should be used to propel or brake the draisine.
The only known information about this draisine is that of the press of the time.
Starting in 1933, Polish artillery began to devote itself to rockets.
The research was carried out by Komórka Techniki Uzbrojenia in collaboration with Professors Mieczyslaw Wolfke and Gustaw Mokrzyckiego.
The documents kept show that this research had reached the testing stage.
Of course, with the arrival of the German armies, the search stopped.
In 1937, plans for a photoelectric hunting rocket, designed by the engineer Rohoziński, appeared in the specialized press and the following year was published the book "Rakieta - torpeda powietrzna i rakietoobomba lotnicza" by an author named Leliwy-Krzywoblocki.
Both projects were designed for military use of rocket engines.
Just before the war, all plans for the use of rocket technology were carried out by the provisional scientific advisory committee ("Tymczasowy Komitet Doradczo-Naukowy"), which coordinated all the work.
This committee had been established in 1937, but after two years of operation, the beginning of the war put an end to its activities.
After the war, further work on aeronautics was published in the Polish press, thanks to the Polish Astronautical Society (Polskie Towarzystwo Astronautyczne).
For the first time, there is a company in the November 1954 issue of Problem, in which four more detailed articles on aeronautics are published.
In one of these articles, written by Professor M. Subotowicze, it is proposed to create a society dedicated to astronautics.
At that time, artificial satellite projects had already been launched and it was clear that space research had a future.
At the beginning of 1956, the Polish Astronautical Society (PTA) made efforts to enter the international Astronautical Federation (created in 1951) and in the autumn, the PTA became a regular member.
The following year, the first president of the PTA, Kazimierz Zarankiewicz (1902 - 1959), became vice-president of the International Astronautical Federation.
He remained in office until his death in 1959.
Starting in 1956, the PTA made a significant contribution to the successful development of the RM meteorological rocket (Rakieta Meteorologiczna), which became the first Polish rocket to conduct scientific research.
The first model, RM-1, was completed in 1957 and the first launch took place on October 10, 1958.
This rocket with a range of 1800 meters had a length of 80 cm and weighed a little less than 5 kg.
Subsequently an improved version was built, RM-1A, and during the summer of 1959 tests of the two-stage RM-2 rocket were started in the Bledov Desert.
This rocket was 1.4 metres long and probably weighed 11.5 kg.
The next prototype should have been able to perform concrete scientific work - the RM-34 rocket should have had a range of up to 14.5 km and should have been used to observe the wind at altitude.
But in 1963, all development work was stopped.
The Meteor-1 rocket developed during the period 1962 - 1965, succeeded the first RM rockets.
This rocket, designed with two stages, had a total length of 510 cm and an initial weight of 32.5 kg.
Three models (called Meteor-1A, -1B and -1C) were developed; they distinguished themselves by the dimensions of the space reserved for scientific tools.
The Meteor-1A rocket had a space offering a volume of 0.4 liter, while in Meteor-1B the volume was 0.34 liter and in Meteor-1C 0.62 liter.
The maximum range of all these types of gear was 37 km.
In the period 1965 - 1968, the Meteor-2 rockets were developed in the Aeronautical Institute, the first flight tests began in October 1970.
The Meteor-2 rocket had an initial weight of 380 kg and was capable of carrying a payload of 10 kg at an altitude of approximately 60 km.
The Meteor-2H and Meteor-3 versions were later built.
Poland's entry into the Committee for Space Research (COSPAR) in 1960 and the creation of a national COSPAR committee two years later are worth mentioning.
Under the Interkosmos programme, Poland also participated in space exploration on artificial Soviet satellites and, in 1978, pilot Miroslaw Hermaszewski became, after Vladimír Remek, the second non-Soviet cosmonaut of this programme.
The repeal of the Public Works Act is not a solution.
Last week, the Constitutional Court repealed the Public Works Act.
This decision raised a lively debate in the public opinion.
It is undoubtedly interesting to look at this issue from a broader perspective.
Liberalist-oriented economic systems, both in the EU and in the context of globalisation, are based on the principle of more unregulated economic competition.
This means in concrete terms that the different economic entities and national economic systems are constantly in conflict with each other.
This is the result of the principle of free trade and free movement (without limits) of private capital combined with unbridled financial speculation.
The considerable differences in labour prices (wages) create a pressure on prices.
The meaning of the term is as follows: a producer tries by importing goods sold at low prices to resist economic competition by "making the price of the competitor more expensive", with the aim of removing a greater share of the market and thus increasing its own profits.
On a large scale, this means for most entrepreneurs: either transferring production abroad, buying cheaply or disappearing. The result is high unemployment in countries where labour prices are high compared to other economies.
Since private capital has no social responsibility and therefore no responsibility for the unemployment it generates, the State's social charges necessarily increase.
This whole situation is intensifying the perfect unwillingness of the entrepreneurs to pay taxes and thus compensate the economic and social damage caused to society as a whole by this race for profit.
This situation is so well known that it is not necessary to provide concrete statistical data.
Unscrupulous practices of private capital create a situation in the different economies in which the governments of the different countries are forced to engage in mutual competition in order to artificially lower the social level of their own population in order to attract foreign capital to their homes.
In other words, governments put their own people at the mercy of private capital without taking into account the social collapse.
This is mainly reflected in the amendments to existing laws.
The aim is to force its own population economically to accept the diktat of private capital prices, especially in the area of wages.
This is due, on the one hand, to a system of economic constraints in the event of long-term unemployment and, on the other hand, to the restriction of workers' rights in the field of labour legislation.
The result is growing poverty and deepening the differences between the rich and the poor.
In the Federal Republic of Germany, for years there have been public food distribution points for the poor who cannot support themselves with their own work.
There are already millions of these people.
In the context of increasing the competitiveness of the German economy, it is becoming quite common for employees to receive such wages that the State is forced to pay a supplement to reach the minimum subsistence level.
Such a scandal has been brought to light, for example, in the case of employees working as auxiliaries to the federal parliament.
The economic measures of almost all the southern EU Member States undoubtedly generate a similar situation in which, under pressure of a catastrophic collapse of society, people are forced either to emigrate (as in the 19th century) or to live with poverty wages, on the margins of society, in the hope that one day private capital will invest in their country.
The question here is: where will this capital come from?
If it comes from other EU countries, then poverty will change from one country to another; this capital may not come either, or then a Chinese, Indian, Brazilian, Turkish, Moroccan, Egyptian or African will continue to work for a fraction of a European salary.
This also applies to the whole of Latin America.
Liberal theory and the media claim that the state cannot make capital investments in its own economy, that the directed economy leads to an economic catastrophe.
Private capital strongly defends the idea that the State cannot intervene in the economy through regulatory intervention.
We must then ask ourselves whether private capital does not influence and, even, does not control today, according to its own selfish interests, politics and by the same token, the entire state.
The answer to this question is undoubtedly yes.
The evidence is that there is a virtually all-powerful lobby in all states.
The result is a desperate situation in the area of corruption, through the granting of mutual benefits, in legislation, where everything is condemnable but not punishable.
In the Federal Republic of Germany, the situation is such that, due to the lack of financial resources, national ministries delegate the drafting of legislation to law firms closely linked to industry.
These bills are then adopted in the Bundestag.
The totality of power does not come from the people, as Western constitutions state, but from powerful financial groups serving their own interests.
It is clear that liberalist-oriented democracies are now quickly confronted with the situation described by Appianos in his book entitled "The Crisis of the Roman Empire in the Times of Caesar and Pompey": "The State had long since been in disrepair and functions were attributed by violence.
The bribes, the favours obtained illegally, and the stones and swords were also used to obtain these posts.
The under-tables and corruption were proliferating without limits and the people were going to the elections with already sold votes" ... ... "The honest people were not trying to get jobs, it resulted once the state remained 8 months without consuls". ... "It was really beginning to say that the remedy to this difficult situation was an autocracy and that one had to choose an energetic man" ... It is true that Appianos had Pompey in mind, but it was Caesar who irreversibly transformed democracy into an absolutist regime.
In conclusion, as in antiquity, the present society is based on the preference of personal profit, without regard for the interest of society as a whole.
In its essence, private capital is no longer capable of understanding and asserting the interests of society as a whole.
Today, as in the past, the result is an unprecedented decadence of elites, without any effort to carry out profound reforms.
We must therefore seek the causes of the emergence of fascist and communist regimes in the unscrupulous liberalization of the economic systems of the nineteenth and twentieth centuries.
In the present state of affairs, the disappearance of these systems in favour of liberal democracies can be seen as a sort of pause before a new stage.
The fact that the current elites are completely unaware of the possibility of hundreds of thousands of future loss of life, the humanitarian and social crises that we are witnessing today, as well as the crimes against humanity as we know them from past and recent history.
The repeal of the Public Works Act is not a solution, at least in the long term.
Under pressure from economic competition, both internationally and internally, the Government of the Czech Republic will be forced to continue to seek ways to reduce the social level of the population.
This trend is indeed systemic.
The solution consists of socio-political reforms, which will strengthen the state's capital investment in the economy, increase the influence of citizens on the government and weaken the monopoly position of private capital in society for the benefit of the state.
