The hardest job in the world: Kawah Ijen's human mule
For four euros, the carriers of the Indonesian volcano risk their life and health by carrying 70 kilos of sulphur through steep stone paths.
There are people for whom work is hell and others who literally work in hell.
This is the case of Anto Wijaya, one of the 400 miners who earn their living by carrying sulphur from the Kawah Ijen volcano, east of the Indonesian island of Java.
It has to work every day to the bottom of the crater, where the sulphuric gas emanating from the entrails of the earth solidifies in contact with the air.
After collecting large sulphur rocks, which weigh a total of nearly 70 kilos, he installs them in two bamboo baskets that he loads on his shoulders through the steep paths.
There are only 250 meters to the peak of the volcano that peaks at 2,386 meters of altitude, but the exhausted carriers take more than 40 minutes to climb this distance, at a tortoise pace, keeping the balance and measuring their steps so as not to stumble and fall into the precipice.
They know that a false step could cost them their lives, as happened to a French tourist who made a fatal fall in the Kawah Ijen volcano several years ago.
The Kawah Ijen miners earn 5 cents of euro for each kilo of sulphur extracted.
Once at the top, he made a way between the tourists who photograph them as if they were circus beasts, and painfully carrying the heavy baskets, they walk the 3 kilometers to the scale that a mining company installed a little below at 1,850 meters of altitude.
It is PT Candi Ngrimbi, a company that has been operating the volcano since 1960 and, it can be said, its employees, to whom it pays 662 Indonesian rupees (5 cents of euro) per kilo of sulphur.
She then sells it to the petrochemical industry at 10,000 rupees (83 cents of euro), since this ore is very present in everyday life and is used to make candles, fireworks, cosmetics, dynamite and even to bleach sugar.
"As we carry about 70 kilos, we earn about 46,000 rupees (3.8 euros) on each trip," explains Anto, who usually makes three trips a day.
Each takes him 3 hours and he finishes exhausted, but this allows him to earn 138,000 rupees (11.50 euros) at the end of the day.
Although it seems to be a misery for such a superhuman effort, it is the triple of what it would gain in the fields.
"The income of the miners is very high here, where the coffee harvest is paid 15,000 rupees (1.20 euros) per day and where the average monthly wage is two million rupees (167 euros)", says the bearer who used to work as a mason on the tourist island of Bali.
There, his salary was 75,000 rupees (6.20 euros) a day and the job was not as difficult, but Anto returned to his family in Banyuwangi, a village near the volcano, for a reason that, in Indonesia, is as indisputable as sulfur: "I married a young girl from Bali, where they are Hindus, and I brought her back to Java to convert to Islam."
Anto suffers from asthma, breathes with difficulty, coughs constantly and her eyes are irritated by toxic gases.
At the age of 27, he spent three of his life defying the danger on the Kawah ljen, but sulphur has already begun to charge him the bill although he covers his face with a mask and wears special gloves.
Anto suffers from asthma, breathes with difficulty, coughs constantly and her eyes are irritated by toxic gases released by the volcano.
That's the price he has to pay to pursue his dream.
"I'm going to work for another two years, because I want to open a shop or study Spanish or French," he promises in an English that is more than acceptable.
Misled by life, this friendly and intelligent young man could be a tourist guide, waiter or receptionist in a hotel, but instead he does the work of a mule.
It shares an unsanitary wood massure with other carriers, rises every day at two o'clock in the morning because sulphur does not cease to spring at night, when its characteristic yellow color becomes blue and shines in the midst of darkness.
Defying the darkness, Anto descends into the crater by lighting himself with a small lamp attached to his helmet, which he bought himself with his own money.
Some 400 carriers load the baskets of sulphur on their shoulders from the bottom of the crater.
Despite its comfortable profits, the mining company has not mechanized the extraction of sulphur to save costs and does not provide any equipment to carriers who work for themselves and are paid by weight.
Moreover, they also do not receive a sub of the 30,000 rupees (2,50 euros) of increase per camera, in addition to the entrance of 15,000 rupees (1,20 euros), that the guards of this natural park charge to the tourists who come to photograph the volcano and its human mules.
"This work is done for animals, not for humans," protestes Madrusin, a 42-year-old corpulent carrier who has been working in Kawah Ijen for thirty years since he left college.
Capable of carrying up to 110 kilos, he assures that he will not stop working "as long as he can", because he needs money to raise his 3 sons, aged between 10 and 18.
I won't retire, I'll die here because the volcano is my whole life.
