The Unasur Summit ended without the Lima Declaration being made public
The Sixth Presidential Summit of the Union of South American Nations (Unasur) ended today in Peru without the Lima Declaration being made public, although it was announced earlier and theoretically adopted by the seven representatives present.
Efe has tried several times to access the document signed at the Sixth Ordinary Meeting of the Unasur Heads of State and Government, but the Ministry of Foreign Affairs and the Presidency initially reported that it would be disclosed after the closure of the summit, and then said that it would be published from one moment to the next on the Peruvian government's website.
When questioned on the text, they reported that its contents had been exposed by the President of Peru, Ollante Humala, in brief statements to the press.
Journalists' access to summit information has been constantly limited.
During the day, only the video without the sound of the presidential assembly with the message "private session, restricted audio" was broadcast in the press room.
The little information circulated between journalists was that given by press officers of some of the Unasur governments attending the meeting, with the exception of the Peruvian spokesman.
The only document released during the day was the list of presidents present, which caused some unease among hundreds of journalists from various national and international media who were calling for more important information.
Later, the presidency of Peru sent an e-mail to the media with the "final declaration" of the summit, but it was President Humala's speech and not the official document that concluded the summit.
Last October, Peru hosted the 3rd South America-Arab Summit (ASPA) and, on that occasion, although it was requested with the press, it had also not circulated the statement called the Lima Declaration, as previously announced.
On the official ASPA website, it can be verified that the document was published last March.
In both international meetings, the Peruvian authorities tried to set up safe transmission systems for all journalists, but they limited their access to information to the maximum extent possible.
The summit also concluded with the joint agreement between Chile and Peru to accept a judgment of the Hague Court which divides a different border between the two countries.
The presidents of Peru, Ollanta Humala, and Chile, Sebastián Piñera, met at the regional meeting and declared that they would respect the ICJ's decision to hear the pleas of both parties in the Lima trial against Santiago, which begins on Monday in The Hague.
"We will respect and execute the verdict that will resolve the disputes we are bringing before this international court today," said President Humala, alongside his Chilean counterpart.
"Chile has always been, and will continue to be, a country that respects international law, the peaceful resolution of controversies, treaties and international tribunals," added President Piñera, giving a handshake to President Humala, next to the flags of both countries.
The confirmation of the two presidents that they would submit to the ICJ took place after Colombia had denounced this week the Pact of Bogota by which it had agreed to submit to the decisions of that international tribunal, after a decision on maritime boundaries with Nicaragua which it considered to be gravely wrong.
The summit was held without the presence of the presidents of Brazil, Dilma Rouseff, Venezuela, Hugo Chávez, Bolivia, Evo Morales, and Argentina, Cristina Kirchner.
Paraguay, suspended from Unasur since 2011 after the dismissal of its former president Fernando Lugo, did not participate in the meeting.
The host President, Ollanta Humala, was instructed to open the proceedings in the morning and close the summit shortly after noon in Lima.
The representative read the final document in which he announced that 16 agreements had been adopted and that the lines of action for 31 projects had been established between South American countries for a total of $17 million in investment.
Among the agreements adopted, he mentioned that the Unasur countries would put in place "important steps to achieve the goal of South American citizenship by developing agreements on residence permits".
He informed that actions would be put in place to improve "cooperation in the fight against urban insecurity and international organized crime, actions to improve access to medicines, access to low-cost Internet throughout South America, and to jointly and effectively assess the risks of natural disasters".
With a Europe in crisis, "economic consolidation (of Latin America) must not have a triumphalistic matrix but must help to increase our productive matrix and to see a better future for our populations", concluded President Humala.
"We decided to focus on a group of 31 emblematic projects that improve the connection of South America's spaces, especially in rural and border areas... by uniting our countries and generating new economic circuits," said the Peruvian President in a speech.
Of these projects, he mentioned that five concerned Peru and were located on the transverse axes of his territory, from the coast to Brazil, and that two were aimed at a larger connection with Ecuador, although he did not provide further details.
Similarly, the outcome document referred to the political situation in Paraguay.
"We hope that this country's electoral process will allow its reintegration into the Union of South American Nations", from which it is currently excluded.
The need for Latin America to remain a region of prosperity and peace, integrated and having good relations with its neighbours, is another theme addressed at the summit.
In this sense, the Colombian president, Juan Manuel Santos, declared, before starting the regional meeting, that he hoped to meet his counterpart of Nicaragua, Daniel Ortega, the following Saturday in Mexico to discuss calmly the maritime dispute through a judgment of the ICJ requested by Bogota.
"It is possible that tomorrow (Saturday) I have a meeting with President Daniel Ortega," said President Santos.
"We are going to review all these ways, they are not exhaustive, including the treaty with Nicaragua which will ask for a discussion with that country," he stressed.
"I hope I can tell President Ortega that we will deal with this in the most civilized and respectful way possible," added President Santos.
Presidents Santos and Ortega will meet on Saturday in Mexico City where they plan to attend the takeover of the new president of that country, Enrique Peña Nieto.
Similarly, in the context of the summit, the Bloc Defence Ministers will meet in advance to approve the 2013 Action Plan, which seeks to strengthen dialogue and consensus in terms of defence in the region.
Argentina, Bolivia, Colombia, Ecuador, Peru, Brazil, Uruguay, Venezuela, Chile, Guyana, Suriname and Paraguay are members of Unasur, although the latter country is suspended.
Peru holds the pro tempore presidency of the regional bloc.
