The insurance remedy will demand non-prosperity and requires review of the trial by a higher court, in this case the Supreme Court of Justice of the United States.
The most serious is that the court ignored a document sent by the Mexican government on behalf of the amicus curiae ("friend of the Court") in which Vitro's procedure under the Commercial Bankruptcy Act was detailed, pointing out that it freed him from the agreements signed by the two countries to bring it to the same level as paragraph 15 of the United States Bankruptcy Act.
In addition, he pointed out that the country had adhered to the principles of the United Nations Commission on International Trade, i.e., the rules for cross-border insolvency cases, which ensured fairness for debtors and creditors.
Carambolage of two parts: they sit on Vitro and they sit on the country.
